Moral Dilemmas for Fannie and Freddie
NEW HAVEN: The takeover of the mortgage giants Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac by the US government represents an enormous bailout of the creditors of these institutions, whose losses had been swelling further in the face of falling house prices.
Now that the government is completely liable for Fannie's and Freddie's debts, American taxpayers will have to pay for everything that is not covered by the insufficient financial means of their creditors.
Why such a rescue action in the most overtly capitalist country in the world?
Do not the venerable principles of capitalism include the fact that those who believed in the housing bubble and invested their money in Fannie and Freddie must now accept their losses?
Is it fair that now innocent taxpayers have to suffer for their mistakes?
The answers to these questions would be obvious if the moral problems of the current financial crisis were clearly defined.
But they are not.
Most importantly, it is unclear whether the bailout will actually cost US taxpayers in the long run. Perhaps it will prevent further systemic effects that would force the financial sector and thus the global economy to its knees.
Just because systemic effects are difficult to quantify, one cannot conclude that they do not exist.
The bonds issued by Fannie and Freddie were widely regarded as being backed by an implicit guarantee of the US government.
Although there was no official guarantee, the lack of a bailout by the US government could undermine trust in government securities and, because they are associated with them, also in other financial instruments.
The problems extend far beyond the US economy.
The global economy has been driven in recent years by remarkable speculative highs and crashes in asset values, which raises questions of trust, but also fairness.
Similar housing sector bubbles are also coming to an end in many other countries, and they may be facing the same torments – and the same moral dilemmas – that the US economy is currently going through.
And the problem is not just the housing markets.
The stock markets are also a problem.
The Chinese Shanghai Composite Index rose by a factor of 5 between 2005 and 2007 and then lost two-thirds of its real value.
The Sensex in India rose real by a factor of 5 between 2003 and 2007 and has since lost a third of its value.
Similar highs and crashes in the stock markets have occurred in many other countries.
As long as they lasted, the boom phases preceding these crashes led to overheating of these economies.
Now that they have reversed, a decline in trust could affect the global economy and push it into recession.
To prevent this, some selected bailouts may be necessary – not to support the market, but to address injustices.
There is no precise science of trust, no way to predict how people will react when, in the face of collapsing markets, help is absent.
The public's reactions to these events depend on their feelings and sense of justice.
The described highs and crashes have caused a significant redistribution of wealth.
Those who invested in the stock market or the housing market made out well or poorly depending on the timing.
People will evaluate the fairness of these results based on what was told to them and the implicit promises they drew from it.
What was told to people in all these countries about the markets into which they invested their money?
Did everything really correspond to the truth?
There is unfortunately no way to find out.
The politics can only react generally and not treat all cases individually.
We know that the recent economic growth in many countries was spectacular.
But were the capital investments in their markets sold too dearly?
Did cynical sellers here and elsewhere deceive people into believing that the boom times would bring prosperity for all?
It is certain that, although there may have been a lot of "cheap talk" – general advice with reservations –, most of the losers in this game will not starve.
However, we cannot close our eyes to the fact that we should not let them suffer all their losses unrestricted.
The nagging problem is one of "faith and trust".
Economies flourish only when "faith and trust" prevail.
The current situation, in which speculative highs drove the global economy – and now, after their collapse, are driving it into recession –, suggests that people who promoted certain investments did so in bad faith.
Let's consider the investors who purchased bonds from Fannie and Freddie.
Although the US government never officially promised to bail them out, it created a special agency, the Office of Federal Housing Enterprise Oversight, whose task was to evaluate their strength in an annual report.
However, this agency never even admitted that there was a housing bubble.
The government leaders never issued a warning.
Can we really claim that the investors must bear all the consequences of their losses?
How could this be fair?
The world is discovering capitalism and its power to transform economies.
However, capitalism relies on trust and faith.
An unfair treatment can be fatal to economic growth, as it means people will lose their trust in companies and be less willing to provide them with their valuable capital and labor.
Is such an outcome morally preferable to a bailout?
